Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | API | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|---|
| `RunLoop()` | `while (true)` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` check |
| `RunLoop()` | `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call interruption | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | Fallback kill | Remove — cooperative cancellation handles it |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns 0 if _newEvent signaled, 1 if cancellation requested
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes a race in the original code where
            // multiple rapid Enqueue calls could be collapsed into one signal)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // wakes WaitHandle.WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` / `Thread.Interrupt()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — Both are gone. Cancelling the token source signals `token.WaitHandle`, which wakes `WaitAny` immediately. No force-kill needed.

2. **`WaitOne()` → `WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles)`** — Waits on *both* the event and the cancellation token, so the thread wakes for new work *or* shutdown.

3. **`while (true)` → `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)`** — The loop cooperates with cancellation at every iteration.

4. **Added `IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` both leak timers/handles if not disposed.

## Bug Fixed in Original Code

The original had a race condition: two rapid `Enqueue` calls would both call `Set()`, but `Reset()` + single `Dequeue()` meant the second item could sit in the queue with no signal to process it. The migrated version drains the queue after each signal.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Keeping `Thread.Abort()` as a "safety net" | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. There is no fallback — cooperative cancellation must work. |
| Not waking the blocked `WaitOne` | If you only cancel the token without including `token.WaitHandle` in `WaitAny`, the thread stays blocked forever. |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks internal timer and registered callbacks. Always `Dispose()`. |
| Calling `Stop()` without `Join()` | The thread may still be mid-`Handle()`. `Join` ensures graceful completion of in-flight work. |
